# /. 1.5 ‘mailabbrev’
====================

‘mailabbrev’ is Emacs’s “abbrev-expansion of mail aliases”, and it is
part of Emacs.  It stores all information in a ‘mailrc’ file, whose
location, and name can be configured via the variable
‘mail-personal-alias-file’ (which see).  The ‘mailrc’ file has the same
format as the ‘mail’ and ‘mailx’ commands use for their startup
configuration file.  ‘mailabbrev’ processes ‘alias’, and ‘source’
statements in the ‘mailrc’ file.  ‘alias’ statements can define simple
aliases and distribution lists, and can be nested in that the alias
expansion can contain references to other alias definitions.  Forward
references, that is references to aliases before they are actually
defined, are possible, too.

   Originally, ‘mailabbrev’ was designed to be used with ‘abbrev-mode’.
The ‘mailabbrev’ EUDC backend does not use ‘abbrev-mode’, but queries
‘mailabbrev’ for alias entries only, and returns these as EUDC results.
All entries where the alias name exactly equals either the ‘email’,
‘name’, or ‘firstname’ attribute value in the EUDC query, will be
returned as matches.  When a ‘mailrc’ alias defines a distribution list,
that is it expands to more than one email address, the EUDC result will
contain a single entry, which will contain an email attribute only,
whose value will be a comma-separated list of RFC 5322 formatted
recipient specifications.


